  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I get background music without vocals for any song?",
  "response": "Obtaining instrumental versions of songs can be done in several ways. Here are some approaches to find background music without vocals:\n\n1. **Streaming Services:**\n   - Many music streaming platforms (like Spotify, Apple Music, or YouTube Music) offer instrumental playlists or albums. You can search for the song's name followed by \"instrumental\" to find versions without vocals.\n\n2. **Official Instrumental Albums/Tracks:**\n   - Some artists release official instrumental versions of their albums. Check the artist's website or platforms like iTunes or Amazon Music for these versions.\n\n3. **YouTube:**\n   - Search for \"Song Title Instrumental\" or \"Instrumental Cover\" on YouTube. There are often channels dedicated to providing karaoke or instrumental versions of popular songs.\n\n4. **Karaoke Tracks:**\n   - Many karaoke apps and websites provide instrumental tracks that can be used as background music. Websites like Karaoke Version or Karafun might have what you need.\n\n5. **Music Licensing Platforms:**\n   - If you're looking for background music for a project, platforms like Epidemic Sound, Artlist, and Audiojungle offer tracks that can be licensed for use.\n\n6. **Editing Software:**\n   - Software like Audacity can sometimes help remove vocals from songs, although the results can vary depending on the track. This method involves techniques like phase inversion but may not always produce a clean instrumental version.\n\n7. **Remix Websites:**\n   - Websites like RemixHold or Splice sometimes provide stems for songs, allowing you to isolate instrumental parts.\n\n8. **Contacting the Artist:**\n   - If you're interested in a specific track, reaching out to the artist or their record label might yield access to an instrumental version.\n\nAlways ensure you have the necessary rights or licenses to use the music, especially for commercial purposes.",
